UID:pen-presents-salt-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T221543Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260531
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260601
SUMMARY:Deadline: PEN Presents x SALT: Sample Translation Grants 2026 (Sout
 h Asian languages)
DESCRIPTION:Special PEN Presents round in partnership with SALT\, funding s
 ample translations from South Asian languages to help unpublished works fi
 nd English-language publishers. The scheme pays for the sample-translation
  work that is usually unpaid. ELIGIBILITY: individual literary translators
  at any career stage\, working from source languages of Bangladesh\, Bhuta
 n\, India\, the Maldives\, Nepal\, Pakistan or Sri Lanka. Apply via the En
 glish PEN PEN Presents page.\n\nOrganisation: English PEN\, in partnership
  with SALT\nLocation: Remote (worldwide translators\; source works in Sout
 h Asian languages)\nAward: GBP 500 to each of 24 shortlisted translators f
 or a 5\,000-word sample translation\; 12 winners additionally receive edit
 orial support and promotion. No application fee.\nDuration: One-off sample
 -translation commission\n\nMore: https://www.englishpen.org/translation/pe
 n-presents/apply-to-pen-presents/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&ut
 m_medium=referral
URL:https://www.englishpen.org/translation/pen-presents/apply-to-pen-presen
 ts/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote (worldwide translators\; source works in South Asian langua
 ges)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:tractor-beam-water-issue-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T221543Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: Tractor Beam: Issue 6 'The Water Issue' - Call for Submis
 sions
DESCRIPTION:Tractor Beam's sixth issue\, themed around water in soil\, grow
 th\, land and ecosystems large and small\, is open for submissions. Editor
 s are seeking anti-apocalyptic visions that explore the future of water in
  farming and food production\, island ecologies\, hybrid sea-soil technolo
 gies\, the people who move water and the people water moves\, plus stories
  about drought\, diaspora and what gets carried downstream. FORMAT: storie
 s under 6\,000 words\; comics 12-16 panels. Submissions accepted via the c
 all page on Tractor Beam's Substack.\n\nOrganisation: Tractor Beam\nLocati
 on: Online publication (remote submissions\; geographic eligibility not st
 ated)\nAward: $1\,000 USD per accepted submission. Accepted work is consid
 ered for publication online (Tractor Beam website and Substack) and\, in s
 ome cases\, for one-off printed editions. Stories may also be considered f
 or the Protopian Prize with contributor consent. No submission fee mention
 ed.\nDuration: One-off published piece (no residency component)\n\nMore: h
 ttps://tractorbeamearth.substack.com/p/call-for-submissions-the-water-issu
 e?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://tractorbeamearth.substack.com/p/call-for-submissions-the-water-
 issue?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Online publication (remote submissions\; geographic eligibility no
 t stated)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:berggruen-prize-essay-competition-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T221543Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260817
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260818
SUMMARY:Deadline: Berggruen Prize Essay Competition 2026: A New Axial Age?
DESCRIPTION:Annual essay competition from the Berggruen Institute\, a compa
 nion to the Berggruen Prize for Philosophy & Culture\, seeking new thinkin
 g and cross-cultural perspectives on fundamental philosophical questions o
 f significance for contemporary life and the future. It looks for essays i
 n the tradition of Rousseau\, Montaigne\, and Emerson (models cited includ
 e Frankfurt\, Nagel\, Sontag\, Fukuyama\, and recent Noema pieces)\, not p
 eer-reviewed academic work: novel ideas\, clearly argued in compelling way
 s for intellectually serious readers. THEME for 2026: 'A New Axial Age?' R
 eferencing Karl Jaspers's Axial Age (c. 800-200 BCE)\, the prompt asks whe
 ther civilisation is again at a 'hinge of history' undergoing a pivotal tr
 ansformation of consciousness driven by rapid technological change and its
  social\, economic\, and political consequences. Suggested (non-exhaustive
 ) angles: the foundational ideas and institutions underpinning present and
  future societies\; the philosophical implications of the current era\; th
 e future of human evolution and life amid the ecological crisis\; shared c
 onceptual foundations for a common future\; global transformation driven b
 y technology and the rise of AI\; the end of the global order and its rami
 fications\; and the future of life amid biotechnology and synthetic life. 
 Entrants may choose their own topic\; for 2026 creative fiction is accepte
 d. ELIGIBILITY: open to the public\; not for academic papers and not gover
 ned by academic disciplinary standards or affiliations. Length up to 10\,0
 00 words in English or 15\,000 characters in Chinese (excluding diagrams\,
  tables\, endnotes\, bibliography\, or authorship declaration). One submis
 sion per year per entrant\, in either English or Chinese\; co-authorship a
 llowed. Submissions must be original and previously unpublished. AI USAGE:
  generative AI must not be used to create content or substitute original t
 hought\, and entrants must engage primary sources rather than AI summaries
 \; AI is permitted only for proofreading/grammar\, as quoted supporting ma
 terial when AI itself is the subject of the research\, or for translating 
 an essay into English or Chinese\, and all AI use (including AI-assisted t
 ranslation) must be disclosed on the front page or the entry is disqualifi
 ed. JUDGING: originality\, clarity\, and style. Essays are due by 23:59 PT
  on 17 August 2026\; PDF only. Chinese-language submissions use a separate
  page. Inquiries to essay@berggruen.org.\n\nOrganisation: Berggruen Instit
 ute\nLocation: Remote/online\; open to the public worldwide (English and C
 hinese submissions)\nAward: USD 50\,000 for the winning English essay and 
 USD 50\,000 for the winning Chinese essay. If there is more than one winne
 r in a language category\, the prize is split evenly. Winning essays are p
 ublished through BI Press or Noema. No entry fee.\nDuration: One-off compe
 tition\; submissions open 17 March 2026 and close 17 August 2026\n\nMore: 
 https://berggruen.org/eu/essay-competition-open?utm_source=artificialnouve
 augrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://berggruen.org/eu/essay-competition-open?utm_source=artificialno
 uveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote/online\; open to the public worldwide (English and Chinese 
 submissions)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:pen-heim-translation-fund-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T221543Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260615
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260616
SUMMARY:Deadline: PEN America: PEN/Heim Translation Fund Grants 2026
DESCRIPTION:PEN America's annual grants for in-progress book-length literar
 y translations from any language into English. Up to 10 grants of USD 4\,0
 00 each. Preference for early-career translators and works from underrepre
 sented languages and regions. Eligible genres include fiction\, creative n
 onfiction\, poetry and drama. ELIGIBILITY: translators of any nationality\
 ; the project must be a translation of a book-length work into English\; p
 revious PEN/Heim recipients are eligible after a waiting period. No applic
 ation fee. Apply by 15 June 2026 via PEN America's grants portal.\n\nOrgan
 isation: PEN America\nLocation: Worldwide (translators of any nationality\
 ; project must translate a book-length work into English)\nAward: USD 4\,0
 00 per project (up to 10 awards per year). No application fee.\nDuration: 
 Project-based (book-length literary translation in progress)\n\nMore: http
 s://pen.org/literary-grants/pen-heim-grants/?utm_source=artificialnouveaug
 rantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://pen.org/literary-grants/pen-heim-grants/?utm_source=artificialn
 ouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Worldwide (translators of any nationality\; project must translate
  a book-length work into English)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:blackstone-publishing-novel-initiative-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T221543Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260609
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260610
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Blackstone Publishing Novel Initiative 2026 (with The
  Black List)
DESCRIPTION:A partnership between The Black List and Blackstone Publishing 
 to identify an unpublished manuscript for a $25\,000 publishing deal. The 
 Black List helps Blackstone shortlist outstanding manuscripts submitted on
  blcklst.com during the submission period. Open to manuscripts in all genr
 es\, with particular interest in work that elevates familiar themes (love\
 , adventure\, guilt\, desire\, betrayal\, family\, identity\, obsession) f
 rom fresh\, compelling perspectives\, especially thrillers\, high-concept 
 mysteries\, romances and horror. REQUIREMENTS: post an original manuscript
  on blcklst.com\, receive at least one evaluation while hosted there (once
  evaluated\, a manuscript can be submitted to any eligible partnership at 
 no additional cost)\, and opt in to the program during the submission peri
 od. Submitted manuscripts must not be under contract elsewhere\; no featur
 e\, pilot\, play or musical submissions are eligible. Applicants must be a
 t least 18 and the sole owner of all rights to wholly original material\, 
 and must agree to the Submission Agreement (which includes legally binding
  terms such as arbitration). If selected\, the writer may enter into a boo
 k deal negotiated in good faith. Writing teams are allowed\, but every mem
 ber must comply and all must opt out if any member becomes ineligible. Not
 e: submitting requires being logged in to blcklst.com with an uploaded pro
 ject (the site charges separately for hosting and evaluations). Deadline J
 une 9\, 2026.\n\nOrganisation: The Black List and Blackstone Publishing\nL
 ocation: Online (manuscripts hosted on blcklst.com)\nAward: A $25\,000 pub
 lishing deal with Blackstone Publishing for the selected manuscript.\nDura
 tion: Submission period November 20\, 2025 to June 9\, 2026\n\nMore: https
 ://blcklst.com/programs/blackstone-publishing-novel-initiative?utm_source=
 artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://blcklst.com/programs/blackstone-publishing-novel-initiative?utm
 _source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Online (manuscripts hosted on blcklst.com)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:queen-mary-wasafiri-new-writing-prize-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T221543Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: Queen Mary Wasafiri New Writing Prize 2026
DESCRIPTION:Annual international writing prize from Wasafiri and Queen Mary
  University of London\, with three categories: Poetry\, Fiction\, and Life
  Writing (creative nonfiction). The prize is specifically for writers who 
 have NOT yet published a book-length work\, making it strongly debut-frien
 dly. The Life Writing category suits a self-contained creative-nonfiction 
 piece (for example an extract or essay drawn from a longer project). ELIGI
 BILITY: open to anyone who has not published a complete book\; no restrict
 ions on age\, gender\, nationality or background. Deadline 11:59pm BST\, 3
 0 June 2026. NOTE: entry fee applies (GBP 12/16\, or a subsidised GBP 6).\
 n\nOrganisation: Wasafiri and Queen Mary University of London\nLocation: O
 nline (UK-based\, international entry)\nAward: GBP 1\,000 cash plus print 
 publication for the winner of each category. Entry fee GBP 12 (single) / G
 BP 16 (double)\; a subsidised GBP 6 fee is available with no proof require
 d.\nDuration: Annual prize\n\nMore: https://www.wasafiri.org/writing-prize
 s/queen-mary-wasafiri-new-writing-prize/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.wasafiri.org/writing-prizes/queen-mary-wasafiri-new-writing
 -prize/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Online (UK-based\, international entry)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:prohelvetia-international-promotion-institutions-outside-switzerland-20
 26@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T221543Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: International Promotion: Institutions Outside Switzerland
  (Literature)
DESCRIPTION:Pro Helvetia's international promotion grant (institutions outs
 ide Switzerland variant) supports organizations abroad promoting contempor
 ary Swiss literary works and authors at book fairs\, festivals\, and event
 s (analogue\, digital\, or hybrid). Open to event organizers\, publishing 
 houses\, professional associations\, or digital platforms based outside Sw
 itzerland\; no Swiss residency or nationality is required\, but projects m
 ust feature Swiss books\, authors\, or translators together with Swiss par
 tner organizations. AMOUNT: maximum CHF 25\,000. Deadlines twice a year: 1
  March (23:59 CET) and 1 September (23:59 CEST). Apply via the Pro Helveti
 a portal.\n\nOrganisation: Pro Helvetia (Swiss Arts Council)\nLocation: Ev
 ent organizers\, publishing houses\, professional associations\, and digit
 al platforms based outside Switzerland\; projects must feature Swiss books
 /authors/translators and Swiss partners.\nAward: Maximum CHF 25\,000. No a
 pplication fee.\nDuration: Promotion project featuring Swiss literature\; 
 deadlines twice yearly (1 March and 1 September).\n\nMore: https://prohelv
 etia.ch/en/find-support/international-promotion?utm_source=artificialnouve
 augrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://prohelvetia.ch/en/find-support/international-promotion?utm_sour
 ce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Event organizers\, publishing houses\, professional associations\,
  and digital platforms based outside Switzerland\; projects must feature S
 wiss books/authors/translators and Swiss partners.
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
